This paper discusses the design and implementation of a Starvation-Free Multi-Version Object Based Transactional Memory System (SF-MVOSTM) which is a concurrent programming technique. The paper discusses concurrency control and transactional memory systems, which are typically discussed in the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) and Programming Languages (cs.PL) sub-categories. The paper also discusses the implementation of the SF-MVOSTM, which involves managing multiple versions of data, which is a common technique used in Database Systems (cs.DB). Additionally, the paper discusses the correctness criteria of the SF-MVOSTM, which is related to Software Engineering (cs.SE). Finally, the paper discusses the performance benefits of the SF-MVOSTM, which is related to Operating Systems (cs.OS).
